    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Melatonin Gummies for Adults</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the right melatonin dose for adults?</summary><p>Sleep researchers recommend starting at 0.5-1mg and increasing to a maximum of 3-5mg. MIT research found 0.3mg optimal. Higher doses provide diminishing returns with more side effects.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How accurate is melatonin content in gummies?</summary><p>A 2017 study found melatonin content varied by -83% to +478% from labels. Fewer than 30% of products were within 10% of stated dose. USP or NSF verification is essential.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can melatonin interfere with medications?</summary><p>Yes — blood thinners, immunosuppressants, diabetes medications, seizure medications, and blood pressure medications may interact. Always consult your healthcare provider.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is melatonin safe every night?</summary><p>Short-term nightly use (up to 3 months) is supported by safety data. Long-term data is limited. The AASM does not recommend indefinite use without medical supervision.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Regular vs. extended-release melatonin?</summary><p>Regular for sleep onset insomnia (difficulty falling asleep). Extended-release for sleep maintenance (waking in the night). Some products offer dual-release for both.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does melatonin affect hormones or fertility?</summary><p>At standard doses (0.5-5mg), no clinically significant hormonal effects in short-term studies. As a hormone, long-term high-dose use warrants medical supervision, especially for those trying to conceive.</p></details>

